---
import FrameworkLayout from '../../layouts/FrameworkLayout.astro';
import { url } from '../../utils';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "MedicalWebPage",
  "name": "Phase 2: Preparation — Hospital Acupuncture Implementation",
  "description": "Develop strategies to leverage enablers and address barriers before implementing acupuncture or acupressure in a hospital setting.",
  "url": "https://hospitalacupuncture.com/framework/preparation/",
  "lastReviewed": "2026-04",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Dr Zhen Zheng",
    "affiliation": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "RMIT University" }
  }
};
---

<FrameworkLayout
  title="Preparation"
  description="Develop strategies to leverage enablers and address barriers identified during Exploration."
  phaseNumber={2}
  bottomLine="In this phase, the team turns Phase 1 findings into actionable plans: selecting the right intervention, determining timing, identifying suitable patient groups, revising hospital guidelines, and assigning clear roles. Thorough preparation is what separates a successful rollout from a stalled pilot."
  schema={schema}
>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Phase 2 bridges the gap between understanding (Exploration) and action (Implementation).
    The team develops strategies to use enablers and address barriers identified in Phase 1.
    While this page uses PONV as the primary worked example, every step applies to any
    hospital acupuncture or acupressure programme.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Preparation Items</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Identify appropriate timing for acupuncture/acupressure intervention</li>
    <li>Revise or update hospital guidelines to incorporate the intervention</li>
    <li>Identify and revise relevant clinical documents</li>
    <li>Determine each team member's role (using the CFIR framework)</li>
    <li>Define suitable patient types and procedures</li>
    <li>Address identified barriers with targeted strategies</li>
    <li>Determine who will deliver the intervention, based on timing and setting</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Feasibility -->
  <h2>1. Feasibility of the Selected Intervention</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>FAME Criteria Assessment</summary>
    <p>
      The FAME framework (Pearson et al., 2005) provides a structured way to evaluate whether
      an intervention should proceed to implementation. Each criterion should be assessed for
      your specific clinical context:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Criterion</th><th>Question</th><th>PONV Example Assessment</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Feasibility</strong></td>
          <td>Can it be done in this setting with available resources?</td>
          <td>Acupressure wristbands require minimal training and ~$5 per unit</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Appropriateness</strong></td>
          <td>Does it fit the clinical context and patient population?</td>
          <td>Non-invasive, patient-acceptable, aligns with multimodal guidelines</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Meaningfulness</strong></td>
          <td>Is it valued by patients and clinicians?</td>
          <td>87% patient willingness post-education; 81% of staff would encourage patients</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Effectiveness</strong></td>
          <td>Does the evidence support clinical benefit?</td>
          <td>Cochrane-level evidence: RR 0.68 nausea, 0.60 vomiting <span class="grade grade-high">High</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      For PONV, the assessment concludes that acupressure is a feasible, appropriate, meaningful,
      and effective intervention that should be implemented. Apply this same framework to your
      target condition.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Timing -->
  <h2>2. Timing Considerations</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>When to Deliver the Intervention</summary>
    <p>
      The timing of acupuncture/acupressure delivery depends on the clinical purpose:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Purpose</th><th>Timing</th><th>Considerations</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Prevention</strong></td>
          <td>Pre-operative or immediate post-operative</td>
          <td>Often provided 30 min prior to surgery, or potentially 12&ndash;24 hours beforehand</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Management</strong></td>
          <td>After symptoms appear</td>
          <td>Can be used as adjunct to rescue medication or as standalone intervention</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Timing decisions are influenced by staff availability, surgical scheduling, ward
      workflows, and which staff members will deliver the intervention. For non-surgical
      applications (e.g., emergency department), timing aligns with patient presentation
      and triage flow.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Patient Selection -->
  <h2>3. Patient Risk Factors and Selection</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Identifying Suitable Patient Groups (PONV Example)</summary>
    <p>
      For PONV specifically, high-risk indicators include:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Female gender</li>
      <li>Prior PONV or motion sickness history</li>
      <li>Non-smoker status</li>
      <li>Younger age</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Surgery types with elevated risk include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Cholecystectomy</li>
      <li>Gynaecological procedures</li>
      <li>Laparoscopic procedures</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For other clinical applications, define equivalent inclusion criteria based on condition
      prevalence, severity, and the populations most likely to benefit from acupuncture/acupressure.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Documentation -->
  <h2>4. Documentation and Guidelines</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Documents Requiring Revision</summary>
    <p>
      Integrating acupuncture or acupressure into hospital practice typically requires updates to:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hospital clinical guidelines</strong> &mdash; to include acupuncture/acupressure as a treatment option</li>
      <li><strong>Clinical checklists</strong> &mdash; e.g., PONV risk checklists, pre-operative assessment forms</li>
      <li><strong>Patient education materials</strong> &mdash; information sheets, consent forms</li>
      <li><strong>Operative documentation</strong> &mdash; to record intervention delivery</li>
      <li><strong>Ward documentation</strong> &mdash; nursing observation charts</li>
      <li><strong>Drug charts</strong> &mdash; if the intervention may reduce pharmacological requirements</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Engage your hospital's document governance process early &mdash; approval timelines can
      add weeks or months to your implementation schedule.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Barriers -->
  <h2>5. Addressing Barriers</h2>

  <details open>
    <summary>Primary Barriers and Strategies</summary>
    <p>
      Phase 1 data (staff surveys, readiness assessment) typically surfaces four key barriers.
      The table below maps each barrier to preparation strategies:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Barrier</th><th>Preparation Strategy</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Lack of awareness</strong> regarding existing evidence</td>
          <td>Prepare evidence summaries; schedule educational sessions; identify opinion leaders
          to champion the evidence base</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Insufficient capability</strong></td>
          <td>Design training packages tailored to each professional group; arrange competency
          assessments; plan on-the-job mentoring</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Equipment unavailability</strong></td>
          <td>Source equipment and consumables; negotiate procurement; establish supply chain
          for ongoing use</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Time constraints</strong></td>
          <td>Map intervention delivery onto existing workflows; identify time-neutral integration
          points; present time-burden data (only 38% of surveyed staff viewed acupuncture as
          too time-consuming)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>

  <!-- Team Roles -->
  <h2>6. Team Role Assignment</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Defining Roles Using the CFIR Framework</summary>
    <p>
      The Consolidated Framework for Implementation Research (CFIR) provides a structured approach
      to defining team roles. For each phase of care, clarify:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Who delivers</strong> the intervention (e.g., nurse, acupuncturist, anaesthetist)</li>
      <li><strong>Who monitors</strong> the patient during and after delivery</li>
      <li><strong>Who documents</strong> the intervention and outcomes</li>
      <li><strong>Who escalates</strong> if adverse events occur</li>
      <li><strong>Who audits</strong> compliance and outcomes</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Role assignment should align with the timing decisions made above. Pre-operative delivery
      may involve different staff than ward-based management.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Downloads -->
  <div class="downloads">
    <h3>Phase 2 Resources</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>FAME criteria assessment template</a></li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Sample hospital guideline revision checklist</a></li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Barrier-strategy mapping worksheet</a></li>
      <li><a href={url('/resources/')}>Team role assignment template (CFIR-based)</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

</FrameworkLayout>
